content: The instant feedback on you photos is addictive but Three things you need to know 1) Bring some cash 2) plan to live in the game 3) be ready to be extremely frustrated. In order to have any chance of getting to ALL star level in a challenge you will need to keep you exposure level high. This involves either votong frequently on other photos or using a fill. You earn fills by completlng contests but you earn thm at a pretty slow rate. You can buy them of course. Like I said bring money. Or be preprared to vote about every hour at a miinimum. Eventually with good photos you might find yourself in the top ten percent or so on a contest. Maybe even in first place as I have been a few times. Don't get too excited. The only way to stay there is the swap, and swap and swap again swaps cost game time or money. Here is where th frustration comes in. During the last few hours of a challenge, when most of the voting is happenin, you will just sit there.I have worked my way to the top ten numerous times eve nnumber one a time or two, only to spend two hours right at the end getting no views (Yes I track these things) no points. Even if I get a vote once in a while it is not enough. The result is that you can take whatever position you are in and times that number by four, that is about where you will be at theend of the contest ... The winner will be some guru levl buddy of the guru who crated the challenge. There is one thing you can do, you can swap, and swap and swap, and swap , and swap and hope the new photos get the votes. If you don't swap you will not win, period. And like I saud swaps cost money. I have nothign againt people making money, but this game is the worst sort of salute to capitalism Once you reach expert level it is required that yu get a Guru Pick. Word on the street is this requires that have spent a certian amount of money or your pics won't even be considered by the guru. that definitley seems to be the case. Plus the guru picks come well before the end of the contest so You have to put your best photos in early and the swap them out dutiring the end phase. Which seems counterintuitive. Not saying this game isn't fun, just know going in that it is not what it seems.

the voting system bis HIGHLY flawed! this review is from my experience. this app is a great way to get started with photography as it challenges you to be creative with your photos. the down side is the voting. if your exposure meter isnt full you have zero chance to place decently. ive been in the top ten, then i go to bed and the next morning im a thousand votes behind (without keeping meter full). even when keeping meter full, over night while sleeping i fall far behind. gurus are idiots
replyContent:
All the exposure algorithm does is to make sure everyone gets the same amount of views. 
The reason your photo's exposure slows down is BECAUSE of fairness to other photos that haven't reached that amount yet.
Each photo's exposure will start slowing down once it reaches the top amount of views available per photo in that challenge.

The concept of GuruShots is interesting and completely different from any other photography app. I like the challenges which force you to focus on a specific theme. In addition, the voting feature is really cool if done properly. However, the innovative aspects of GuruShots are also its weak points. If you want to fill the exposure gauge you have to keep voting. Nothing wrong with that if it wasn't for tons of more or less silly selfies that you have to go through (especially in the Newbie challenge) . Together with random photos of pets, feet, kids, and other meaningless stuff. I try my best to vote good shots but it's not easy to find meaningful ones and at the end it can take ages to fill the exposure. This probably also makes the voting system not very genuine: I can imagine people voting on anything just to get the exposure up as quickly as possible. On a side note, the user level seems not working very well: I have about 5,000 gs points and somehow I'm still stuck on newbie level. All in all, GuruShots is an awesome idea which, unfortunately, tends to become tedious easily. Unless you are willing to pay for boosts, of course.

Hi Kyle,
The voting is designed to give every image equal opportunity to get voted on.
New photo gets exposure because the voting system strives to equal out the view across all photos in challenge.
Once you reach the top amount of views your exposure will slow down but at the end all photos in the challenge will have a similar amount of views.

The voting is designed to give every image equal opportunity to get voted on.
New photo gets exposure because the voting system strives to equal out the view across all photos in challenge.
Once you reach the top amount of views your exposure will slow down but at the end all photos in the challenge will have a similar amount of views.

Fundamentally this app is so much fun. Especially since I have discovered

votes. It takes money and timing of clear, precise and on topic images. 
However, there are so very many players that play images that are the same 
subject posed differently. (Example: colored pencils or an animal) what 
makes it all the more frustrating is the fact Champions, Masters and even 
Guru's are too often guilty, even though they are aware of the rule in each 
challenge against this practice. I policed one challenge today and tonight 
to report similars. Everyone has their own perfect reasons for playing this 
app. Mine is to fine-tune my eye for imagery and to think outside the box. 
Though it would be a treat to win, The fun comes in obeying the rules. 
Besides, I often enjoy looking at the places I'm likely never going to 
visit. It would be Grand if the developers of this game would regroup and 
tweak the algorithm to push it players from votes until they give four 
distinctly different subject. Then the game would be fair for all players, 
not just high scoring perfect images because they are on topic. Your losing 
players, why not retain them?

This is my updated portion. Still have a big problem with the Boost a 
picture is climbing super good consistent then you throw on a Boost and all

constantly put off topic pictures on it. You have to sit and scroll for 5

have a problem with the autofill it doesn't seem to auto fill all the 
pictures or challenges I should say. Some don't fill all the way. Some do 
fill and some don't even fill so my opinion still is don't buy anything if 
you want to buy anything by a swap. And always wait so you have a few days 
for a swap. And only boost right when you start or in the last 24 hours.

stuff in. Go out to take some pictures. I still like the game has put a lot 
of perspective into my picture taking. I carry my DSLR Everywhere I Go. 
Before I started playing this game I never even thought of taking pictures

or take a photo. Don't waste your money though on a Boost or the autofill. 
It's a waste of money it's a waste of time. First of all like to start out 
it's kind of a neat concept. But there's a few things I just don't like. 
I've been playing the game for about a month. 1. When you go to boost a 
picture it doesn't seem to work and what I mean by that as soon as you 
spend a boost on a picture that is taken in 200 or so votes and is doing 
really good without a boost. The votes generally stop coming in. And your 
other pictures will get more votes then the one you're boosting. People put 
pictures in that are not even part of the challenge. Or relate to anything 
of the challenge. When you use the autofill for the voting supposed to keep 
it full for the day. After you use autofill voting. Within the hour or so 
you got to vote again what's the purpose of having it if you can't rely on 
that it's going to keep your votes up. It's a useless feature. So don't 
spend money on that. Another problem I have so when you're as you're trying 
to rank up you complete the challenges and in order to rank to a higher 
skill level. Once you've completed the challenge and the requirements. You 
have to wait and tell the challenge is done. For example. When you were at 
Challenger level working away too advanced. You've got to get 10 premiere 
rankings. If you're on the challenge that last 12 days or 10 days you have 
to wait for that to be completed. Instead of once you reach that point of 
getting 10 Premier challenges you should automatically rank up and not have 
to wait until the end of the contest. Currently I am in need of 15 Elite 
levels I currently have nine Elite all ready for the challenge. The 
challenges I'm in already have five and one more soon to hit Elite. Then I 
would go into the next ranking up. But instead I have to wait another 10 or 
12 days for me to rank up. It's stupid. Some of these challenge they come 
up with are stupid. I love photography. And the game could be good. But 
there's a lot of stupid things about it. Don't waste your money on buying 
boost and keys and power ups because they don't work. I'll have an 
Instagram a picture that has three to four thousand likes. And fits the 
challenge perfectly to a T. And it'll get like 20 votes. Picture that 
doesn't even relate to the challenge outperforms me night and day. Got to 
do a better job on getting rid of pictures that don't relate to the 
challenge. Like one challenge recently the orange challenge. There's a guy 
surfing there's nothing orange in the picture there's nothing related to 
the color orange and there's a guy surfing. Or guy working on his car no 
orange in the picture whatsoever. And don't let your kids play this game 
because there's tons of nudity. I'll probably continue to play the game a 
little bit longer hopefully there's some more improvements but. I 
definitely will not spend our damn Penny on this game because none of it 
works.

I love/hate this app. It's gotten me back into photography. But the range of players is extreme. Professional photographers to...well people like my mother-in-law that don't seem to realize they're taking a photo. Slogging through all of that is frustrating. I like to test my skill as a photographer,  not an editor.  I don't have a chance against the higher level professionals because not only do their votes count for more, but many edit to the point that it's not realistic. Fake=beautiful.  I just keep thinking Ansel Adams didn't need more hours in post-processing than processing. I've decided to edit my photos the same way, taking the realism away...and I'm getting more votes. This my love/hate. I know these photos have good composition and lighting. I just have to make the colors stronger than they even are in life. Is that truly photography? It's crazy how many people try to use every challenge to post a mature or violent picture.  I'm afraid to play this game in public because they're not always marked as adult and the kids around me see. The photographer can mark it as adult content themselves, but often they don't and the community has to. I don't need to expose a kid sitting next to me to a half eaten rat or an 'artistic' shot of a naked woman. This was much more prevalent than it should have been during the International Women's Day competition. Instead of seeing women in all walks of life,  the entries were filled with sexy shots of women trying to titallate men. People ignore or twist the challenge descriptions.  The White out challenge...people converted to black and white.  Lens Flares and Sunspots? People obviously don't know what those are. Don't even get me started on people in their native garb being entered into the cosplay challenge. Just insulting. Yet lackluster photos somehow still climb. I did a comparison of a top 20 photo with the same subject as my own. I posted my own voting anonymously.  Mine won by a ratio of 4:1, yet on Guru Shots it wasn't even ranked. Since the higher you go, your votes count for more, when you are in the lower levels the odds of moving up are stacked against you. I've decided to find some other way to challenge my photography and grow. This has left me stagnant and only upped my editing...not my end goal. PS...I am so done with pictures of the moon, flowers with "dew", and jets with colored contrails. Not to mention women in "sexy" poses. It's easy to make a pretty woman pretty. Take a good picture of an average person to show off your skill. ETA- why I will never spend money on this app: baby animals challenge. There's a picture of lamb stew...not even a good picture...and it has the same number of votes as my picture of an actual lamb. Yet it is ranked and mine is not.

For those that think Boosts are pay to win,  read the rules.  We all get one  Boost per challenge.  Just one, and it's free. It is available for 24 hours on a semi random day of the challenge.  All you have to do is log on,  and click the button.  If you want it early,  or missed the window, you may use a Key, but you still only get one Boost. The reason you get a flurry of votes when you first post a pic, and then nothing, is that you only get so many views, and then they give other folks a chance. If those that posted on the first day were available for voting the entire time, then those that post late would have no chance. All our pics, except the boosted one, will get roughly the same number of views, and the cream will rise to the top. Not pay to win.

The reality is they do not get the same amount of exposure, at all. I've submitted a photo at the very beginning of a challenge, as early as possible. There are also irregularities in how the submission rules are inforced. It is a great app for seeing what others are doing, and it is inspiring. But as far as a legitimate photo competition, in no way does this app qualify.

The voting is designed to give every image equal opportunity to get voted on.

replyContent:
Hi 
The voting is designed to give every image equal opportunity to get voted on.
New photo gets exposure is because the voting system strives to equal out the view across all photos in challenge.
Once you reach the top amount of views your exposure will slow down but at the end all photos in the challenge will have a similar amount of views.
